  "stage": {
    "id": "course_3_prediction",
    "stageNumber": 3,
    "title": "Multi-Scale Detection & Prediction",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "multi_scale_prediction",
        "title": "YOLOv3's Core Innovation: Multi-Scale Predictions",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- three detection scales\n- small-large object range\n- independent prediction heads\n\nIn earlier YOLO versions, predictions only happened at one scale (e.g., 7×7 or 13×13). This missed small objects.\n\nYOLOv3's innovation: predict simultaneously at 13×13 (large objects, large receptive field), 26×26 (medium objects), and 52×52 (small objects, fine detail). Each scale has separate detection head, trained jointly. This single change dramatically improved small-object detection, closing the gap to slower detectors.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "anchor_boxes",
        "title": "Anchor Boxes: Predicting Multiple Shapes",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- pre-defined templates\n- aspect ratio diversity\n- shape priors\n\nImagine a 13×13 grid cell. Many different objects could fall in that cell — a person (tall, narrow), a car (wide, short), a ball (square). If we predict just one box per cell, we can't capture all shapes.\n\nYOLOv3 uses 3 anchor boxes per cell, each with different aspect ratios (e.g., 1:1, 2:1, 1:2). This gives 3 shape templates per cell, and the network predicts adjustments to these templates. Total: 3 anchors × 3 scales = 9 predictions per grid cell position across the image.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "grid_prediction",
        "title": "Grid-Based Predictions: Efficient Spatial Encoding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- spatial grid\n- cell-based responsibility\n- fixed output structure\n\nThe 13×13 grid is key to YOLO's speed. Instead of proposing thousands of possible boxes (Faster R-CNN), YOLO divides the image into a 13×13 = 169 cells. Each cell predicts 3 bounding boxes (anchors) and class scores.\n\nThis gives 169 × 3 = 507 total predictions — structured, fixed output. No expensive per-pixel processing, just 169 grid cells making 3 predictions each. It's like tiling the image with prediction \"licenses\" — each cell gets a license to output boxes.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "objectness_score",
        "title": "Objectness Score: Is There an Object Here?",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- logistic regression\n- binary classification\n- confidence score\n\nFor each predicted box, the network outputs a single objectness score (0 to 1) via sigmoid activation: \"What's the probability this box contains an object?\"\n\nThis is different from class prediction (\"Is it a cat, dog, or person?\"). Objectness answers: \"Is there *anything* here?\" A box with objectness=0.9 is highly confident it contains something; objectness=0.1 is uncertain.\n\nDuring inference, boxes with low objectness are discarded, cleaning up predictions.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "bbox_regression",
        "title": "Bounding Box Regression: Precise Localization",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- coordinate offsets\n- anchor adjustment\n- exponential scaling\n\nPredicting absolute coordinates is hard (unbounded). YOLOv3 predicts offsets relative to anchor templates:\n- tx, ty: offsets from grid cell center (via sigmoid to keep in [0, 1])\n- tw, th: log-scale scaling of anchor width/height (via exp transformation)\n\nThis constrains predictions to reasonable ranges and accelerates training. An anchor box for a car (16×32 pixels) with tw=0.5 becomes 32×64 — plausible car sizes. It's like saying \"start with this shape and adjust by this factor.\"",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-3",
      "question": "YOLOv3 predicts bounding boxes by: What's the actual approach?",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "Predicting absolute (x, y, w, h) coordinates directly",
        "Predicting offsets (tx, ty, tw, th) relative to anchor priors",
        "Predicting corner coordinates (x1, y1, x2, y2) for each anchor"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Predicting offsets (tx, ty, tw, th) relative to anchor priors",
